# 3. `InvoiceBatchConfiguration` coverage

This usually means your `@Bean` methods are not directly tested.

You do not need a full Spring test.
Just instantiate config and call bean methods.

Example:

```java
class InvoiceBatchConfigurationTest {

    @Test
    void shouldCreateRetryStep() {
        InvoiceBatchConfiguration config = new InvoiceBatchConfiguration();
        Step step = config.retryFailedTransfersStep(stepBuilderFactory, tasklet);
        assertThat(step).isNotNull();
    }
}
```

If constructor injection makes this awkward, use `@SpringBootTest` only for config coverage:

```java
@SpringBootTest
class InvoiceBatchConfigurationIT {

    @Autowired
    @Qualifier("retryFailedTransfersJob")
    private Job retryJob;

    @Autowired
    @Qualifier("retryFailedTransfersStep")
    private Step retryStep;

    @Test
    void shouldLoadRetryBeans() {
        assertThat(retryJob).isNotNull();
        assertThat(retryStep).isNotNull();
    }
}
```

That is often enough to lift coverage on configuration classes.

